{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3c6f8f5d-e5ff-463b-9a72-e4a7573ddf73","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for **Apple's built-in crash reports**:\n\n1. **Crash Reporter logs** — found at:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS).\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and navigate to **Crash Reports** in the sidebar to browse them with a GUI.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — macOS disables them by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file appears in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n> **Note:** `/cores` requires SIP adjustments or appropriate entitlements on newer macOS versions. The `.ips` crash reports under `DiagnosticReports` are usually the easiest starting point — they include the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"77830fcc-89b1-417f-a5cc-9f109606b44c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":294,"requestId":"DA08:1837D6:51A8E1:5D6136:6A03D866"},"id":"99c5b5c6-e870-4726-8af6-03e182cac897","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:48:31.232Z","parentId":"985534b4-08fb-478d-bb7e-1f81754ebec1"}
